<DOC><DOCNO> AP890809-0024 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0250EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-09 0472</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,480</SECOND><NOTE>Homeless Number Growing, Study Says</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   As many as 14 million families could be forcedinto homelessness by a mild recession in the U.S. economy,according to a study.   The report by the American Affordable Housing Institute saidpublic efforts to help the homeless rely are badly underfinanced,uncoordinated and are conducted by officials often unaware of theresources available to them.   The report by the institute, a research center at RutgersUniversity in New Brunswick, N.J., estimated that there are 4million to 14 million American families ``living on the knife edgeof homelessness'' who could face life on the streets should a mildrecession occur.   ``They are one pay check, one domestic argument from thestreets,'' the report said. ``In a mild recession, homelessness inAmerica is likely to double and triple almost overnight.''   Estimates on the current number of homeless people range between655,000 to 4 million, but the total is growing 20 percent to 40percent annually, the study said.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>CIA Says Turmoil Will Hobble China</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Turmoil in China means the government therewill have a difficult time dealing with inflation and othereconomic problems, the CIA has concluded.   Economic reform has been put on hold by the central governmentand economic problems could prompt renewed political unrest in the1990s, said the report to the Joint Economic Committee releasedTuesday.   ``The new leadership has endorsed a continuation of theausterity program, but the social and political turmoil that hasgripped China since April will make it difficult for Beijing tosolve its pressing economic problems,'' the report said.   Inflation in 1989 hit 19 percent overall and 30 percent in urbanareas, the highest levels since the communists came to power in1949.   The CIA authors also said China's military leaders probably willplay a larger political and economic role in return for themilitary crackdown last May on democracy demonstrations in Beijing.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>FCC Says Prof Filed False License Applications</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Communications Commission suspectsthat a professor at the State University of New York at Oswego wasrunning an ``application mill'' that filed for more than 100broadcast licenses under false or forged names in order to collectsettlement payoffs.   ``You could use that term,'' FCC spokeswoman Patricia Chew saidTuesday discussing the case of Bernard Boozer, of Central Square,N.Y. ``Some of his applications did enter into settlementagreements, if I remember correctly.''   Outgoing FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick sent a letter last weekto the Justice Department asking for an investigation of Boozer.After an investigation, the FCC concluded that Boozer may haveviolated both commission regulations and federal law.   Boozer could not be reached for comment. There was no telephonenumber listed under his name in Central Square, N.Y.</TEXT></DOC>